Even without GPS, phones constantly connect to nearby Wi-Fi and cell towers. Each signal has a known location, so comparing signal strength from multiple sources lets others pinpoint your position within meters. Apps, providers, or silent system processes may use this to track movement. Turning off Wi-Fi or mobile data isn’t always enough—chips can still respond silently. Devices fully disconnected from all networks avoid this kind of tracking. Related terms worth knowing include silent SMS, IMEI logging, passive scans, baseband firmware, and location metadata—especially when thinking about how movement or presence can be mapped without obvious consent.